Subsidy Trap
Cambridge, Massachusetts - No policy has directly opposed good economics and good politics as much as food and energy subsidies have.
Unaffordable subsidies have become the core issue faced by three important new global leaders: Egyptian President Sisi, Indonesian President Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Modi.
The subsidy cuts Sisi faces are needed to be better than expected.
On the other hand, Modi is facing a more severe situation than expected, and may even jeopardize the long-awaited World Trade Organization agreement.
But Zokovic's situation remains unclear.
In July, Sisi accomplished an achievement that few leaders in North Africa and the Middle East could achieve: he significantly reduced the existing energy subsidies, causing prices to rise by 41-78%.
What's strange is that almost no anti-government protests occurred.
Egypt's food subsidy program costs more than $5 billion annually and urgently needs reform.
The bread price has remained at an extremely low level, often being used to feed animals.
In the past, North African countries' efforts to cut such subsidies often sparked unrest, and even toppled governments.
But the Siwa government seems to have made progress in this regard.
The bread subsidy has been reduced by 13%.
Siwa has no other choice.
Even after the subsidy reduction, the current government's next fiscal year's budget deficit target still reached 10% of GDP (would have reached 14% without subsidy reduction).
However, almost no one anticipated that Sisi would be able to act faster than Modi in a politically volatile environment. Modi won the prime minister's seat through an overwhelming democratic majority, as Indians desperately hoped for thorough economic reform.
In Indonesia, President Jokowi inherited a long-standing fuel subsidy of up to 21 billion US dollars per year (equivalent to 20% of government expenditure), which had already weighed heavily on the country.
Jokowi's predecessor, SBY, had taken the courageous first step a year ago by increasing fuel prices.
Jokowi's advisors suggested phasing out the remaining subsidies, and he openly stated that he planned to implement this plan within four years.
Economists confidently opposed commodity subsidies, as the agricultural and energy markets were almost perfectly competitive, with a large number of consumers on the demand side and a large number of producers on the supply side.
In a competitive but imperfect field, it is the government -- not large private monopolies -- that is the root.
Critics of the invisible hand point out that self-regulating private markets may fail in various ways.
Examples of this include income inequality and environmental externalities, which are two of the main reasons for government intervention.
Food and fossil fuel subsidies have been the subject of intense controversy because they are often implemented under the guise of environmental or equality concerns, but in reality, they rarely achieve these goals and often have the opposite effect.
Egypt's food subsidies only gave less than 20% to the poor.
Most countries' gasoline subsidies are fattening the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, only less than 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas subsidies are given to the poorest population, while 52.6% flow into the pockets of the richest groups.
Worldwide, less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies are given to the poorest 20% of the population.
Food and energy subsidies could also distort public policy, and the Modi government, which aims to protect Indian agricultural subsidies, is a clear example.
Actually, the Modi government vetoed WTO compromises that would have made the most important progress in multilateral trade talks over the past decade.
Agricultural subsidies sometimes come from the generosity of producers to benefit consumers, especially in poor countries; and sometimes they come from the generosity of consumers to benefit producers, especially in rich countries.
India's policies, on the other hand, aim to strike a balance.
As a result, India achieved a remarkable feat: providing wheat to consumers at low prices, while also experiencing oversupply, as farmers were able to sell at high prices.
(Farmers also receive subsidies for agricultural inputs – electricity, water, and fertilizers – but this has come at the cost of environmental damage.
) The government bought large quantities of rotten rice and wheat, while the distribution of the limited amount of grain that consumers could get was both corrupt and failed to meet the goal of helping the poor.
Government may continue to maintain subsidies and stockpiling.
But it knows that this will violate the rules of the World Trade Organization.
Since it cannot permanently change these rules, Modi simply vetoed the eagerly anticipated Trade Facilitation Agreement of the World Trade Organization.
Once the subsidies are implemented, it would be difficult to revoke them.
When world commodity prices rise (like in the past decade), citizens who are accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot isolate them from the shock.
But people who are accustomed to government-set prices for food and energy will demand that the government be responsible.
This forms a very strong reason, which from the beginning should not have implemented subsidies.
This doesn't mean that once subsidies are implemented, maintaining subsidies is always the best choice for smart politicians.
If the alternative to rising prices is shortages or rationing, angry opponents may also erupt.
Similarly, if the continuously widened gap ultimately leads to a greater rise in retail prices, leaders who act slowly will also not benefit.
In an ideal situation, measures more efficient than cutting food and energy subsidies should be taken to support lower-income households at the same time.
Developing countries have had considerable experience in effective transfer mechanisms, such as Mexico's Progressa-Oportunidades program and Brazil's Bolsa Família program, which are innovative conditional cash transfers, as well as India's Unique Identification system and other technological innovations.
However, some countries only adjusted their policies when a budget crisis arrived, and they may not have had the money to make transfers to alleviate the pain.
It would be wise for a shrewd politician to implement unpopular adjustments at the beginning of their tenure.
Jokowi and Xi both adopted this approach.
Narendra Modi, who won a landslide victory in the election with the banner of market reform, has already fallen behind.
